Note: ============================================================================
Note: ERLANG PARSER - Production Translation Frontend
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Complete parser for Erlang concurrent functional language
Note: Handles: modules, functions, pattern matching, guards, receive blocks,
Note: list comprehensions, binary syntax, records, type specs, macros
Note: Target: Actor model, message passing, fault-tolerant systems
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIRNodes

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ERLANG AST NODE TYPES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level AST node for an Erlang source file. Erlang modules group
functions, records, and type declarations under a single module name
that is later used for export/import resolution. Attributes are kept
as a separate list (rather than folded into module metadata) so the
later HIR pass can decide which attributes are runtime-visible
(behaviour, on_load) versus documentation-only.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five-field record: module_name extracted from the -module attribute,
attributes as the full ordered list of declared attributes (including
the -module attribute itself for round-trip), functions / records /
types as the ordered lists of definitions in source-declaration order.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangModule":
    module_name as String
    attributes as List[ErlangAttribute]
    functions as List[ErlangFunction]
    records as List[ErlangRecord]
    types as List[ErlangTypeDecl]
End Type

@Reasoning:
Generic attribute record covering every "-keyword(args)" form Erlang
supports (module, export, import, behaviour, compile, ...). The
attr_type tag drives downstream interpretation since each attribute
shape carries a different value structure - keeping attr_values as a
generic List[Any] avoids needing one Type per attribute kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-field record: attr_type (lowercase keyword name), attr_values
(parsed payload - for -export this is a List of {Name, Arity} pairs,
for -module a single string, etc.), line (source line for diagnostics).
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangAttribute":
    attr_type as String           Note: "module", "export", "import", "behaviour", etc.
    attr_values as List[Any]      Note: Attribute-specific values
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Erlang functions are identified by name/arity tuple - the same name
with different arities is a different function. This record groups all
clauses (overloaded patterns) of one name/arity into a single unit so
the HIR can lower each clause as a pattern-match case.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-field record: name (the function name string), arity (number of
formal parameters - all clauses must share the same arity), clauses
(ordered list - clause order matters for pattern matching priority),
line (declaration line for diagnostics).
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangFunction":
    name as String
    arity as Integer
    clauses as List[ErlangFunctionClause]
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
A clause is one pattern-match arm of a function. Erlang's guard
grammar is two-level: top-level "," conjunctions and ";" disjunctions,
so guards is List[List[expr]] - the outer list is OR-joined, the
inner lists are AND-joined. Patterns and body are flat lists of
expressions per the Erlang grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-field record: patterns (one per formal parameter), guards (OR-of-
AND structure - each inner list must all evaluate true; any inner list
succeeding wins), body (expressions evaluated when patterns and guards
match, the last expression's value is the clause result), line.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangFunctionClause":
    patterns as List[ErlangExpression]
    guards as List[List[ErlangExpression]]  Note: [[guard1, guard2], [guard3]]
    body as List[ErlangExpression]
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Erlang records are syntactic sugar over tagged tuples (the first
element of the tuple is the record name atom). The HIR keeps records
as first-class types so the lowering pass can choose between tuple
encoding (default) and target-language struct types where available.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-field record: name (the record name - becomes the leading atom
in the tuple), fields (ordered list of ErlangRecordField; position is
part of the record contract), line.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangRecord":
    name as String
    fields as List[ErlangRecordField]
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Per-field metadata for record definitions. Both default_value and
field_type are optional in Erlang source syntax (#name{} works
without either); when absent they are stored as null/empty
ErlangExpression and ErlangTypeExpr placeholders so the AST has
uniform shape across all fields.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four-field record: name (atom token), default_value (expression used
when the field is omitted at construction time, or null), field_type
(declared type, or null when the type is implicit any()), line.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangRecordField":
    name as String
    default_value as ErlangExpression
    field_type as ErlangTypeExpr
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Unified record for the four Erlang type-system attributes (-type,
-opaque, -spec, -callback) because they share an identical syntactic
shape - only their semantic interpretation differs. decl_type holds
which form was parsed; the HIR lowering selects the right semantic
treatment by inspecting that tag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five-field record: decl_type (one of "type" / "opaque" / "spec" /
"callback"), name, type_vars (parameter type variables for
parameterised types), type_expr (the right-hand side of the
declaration), line.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangTypeDecl":
    decl_type as String          Note: "type", "opaque", "spec", "callback"
    name as String
    type_vars as List[String]
    type_expr as ErlangTypeExpr
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Recursive type-expression node covering every shape Erlang's type
language emits: atomic types (atom, integer, ...), constructors
(tuple, list, fun, union), and references to user-defined types.
type_kind identifies which shape, type_args holds the shape-specific
payload (e.g. element types for tuple, arg+return for fun, alternatives
for union).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-field record: type_kind (string discriminant), type_args
(List[Any] - polymorphic payload; nested ErlangTypeExpr instances for
compound types, raw strings for atom literals), line.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangTypeExpr":
    type_kind as String          Note: "atom", "integer", "tuple", "list", "fun", "union", etc.
    type_args as List[Any]       Note: Type-specific arguments
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Unified expression node that covers the entire Erlang expression
grammar (literals, operators, control constructs, comprehensions,
record operations, macros). Using a single Type with a string
discriminant (expr_type) avoids needing ~20 separate types - the
expr_data Dictionary holds the shape-specific payload keyed by name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three-field record: expr_type (string tag - one of ~20 documented
shapes), expr_data (Dictionary[String, Any] with shape-specific keys
- e.g. atom uses "value", op uses "operator"/"left"/"right", call
uses "function"/"args"), line.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangExpression":
    expr_type as String          Note: "atom", "var", "integer", "float", "string", "list", "tuple", "binary", "fun", "call", "op", "case", "if", "receive", "try", "comprehension", "record_create", "record_access", "macro"
    expr_data as Dictionary[String, Any]
    line as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Stateful parser context that holds the input token stream plus the
cursor + cached current-token state. Caching current_token / lexeme /
line avoids three list-at-index calls on every grammar decision,
which is the hot path of the parser. Errors are collected (not
raised) so the parser produces a best-effort AST plus diagnostic
list even on malformed input.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Eight-field record. The three Lists (tokens, lexemes, line_numbers)
are parallel arrays produced by the lexer and indexed by position.
position is the cursor into them. The three current_* fields are
the cached entries at position (rebuilt by advance_parser).
current_line defaults to 1 for empty input. errors is a List of
diagnostic strings.
@End Implementation
Type called "ErlangParser":
    tokens as List[Integer]      Note: Token types
    lexemes as List[String]      Note: Token text
    line_numbers as List[Integer]       Note: Line numbers
    position as Integer          Note: Current token index
    current_token as Integer     Note: Current token type
    current_lexeme as String     Note: Current token text
    current_line as Integer      Note: Current line number
    errors as List[String]       Note: Parse errors
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PARSER INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Initialises a fresh parser at position 0. Prefetches the first token
into the cached current_* fields so the top-level parse_erlang_module
loop can dispatch on the first token without an extra advance call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates an empty errors_list, constructs the ErlangParser with all
positional defaults, then if the token stream is non-empty seeds
current_token / current_lexeme / current_line from index 0. Empty
input leaves the parser pointing at the implicit EOF (handled by
advance_parser's bounds check).
@End Implementation
Process called "create_erlang_parser" that takes tokens as Integer, lexemes as Integer, line_numbers as Integer returns ErlangParser:
    Let errors_list be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let parser be a value of type ErlangParser with
        tokens as tokens,
        lexemes as lexemes,
        line_numbers as line_numbers,
        position as 0,
        current_token as 0,
        current_lexeme as "",
        current_line as 1,
        errors as errors_list

    Note: Initialize first token
    If length of tokens is greater than 0:
        Set parser.current_token to tokens at index 0
        Set parser.current_lexeme to lexemes at index 0
        Set parser.current_line to line_numbers at index 0
    End If

    Return parser
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOKEN MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Cursor advancement is the hot operation of every recursive-descent
walker in this file. Updates the three cached current_* fields in
one place so callers never read past the end of the parallel arrays;
the EOF synthesis means downstream loops can match TOKEN_EOF
deterministically.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Increments position. If still in bounds, re-reads the three parallel
arrays at the new index into current_token / current_lexeme /
current_line. On out-of-bounds, synthesises TOKEN_EOF with an empty
lexeme; current_line is intentionally left at its prior value so
EOF diagnostics report the last real source line.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_parser" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns Nothing:
    Set parser.position to parser.position plus 1

    If parser.position is less than length of parser.tokens:
        Set parser.current_token to parser.tokens at index parser.position
        Set parser.current_lexeme to parser.lexemes at index parser.position
        Set parser.current_line to parser.line_numbers at index parser.position
    Otherwise:
        Set parser.current_token to TOKEN_EOF
        Set parser.current_lexeme to ""
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read-ahead without advancing the cursor. Used by grammar rules that
need a second token to disambiguate (e.g. distinguishing tuple from
function call after seeing an identifier). Returns TOKEN_EOF past
end-of-input so callers can safely compare against grammar tokens
without bounds-checking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes position + offset. Returns tokens at that index if in bounds,
TOKEN_EOF otherwise.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_token" that takes parser as ErlangParser, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Let next_pos be parser.position plus offset

    If next_pos is less than length of parser.tokens:
        Return parser.tokens at index next_pos
    Otherwise:
        Return TOKEN_EOF
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mandatory-token consumer used at every grammar position where a
specific token is required (commas inside lists, dots ending forms,
etc.). On mismatch it records a diagnostic but does NOT advance,
which is the deliberate choice so the caller can attempt recovery
without skipping potentially-meaningful tokens.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If current_token matches expected, advances and returns true.
Otherwise formats a "Expected <expected> but got <actual> at line N"
message, appends it to parser.errors, and returns false without
advancing.
@End Implementation
Process called "expect_token" that takes parser as ErlangParser, expected as Integer returns Boolean:
    If parser.current_token is equal to expected:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Let error_msg be "Expected token " joined with string representation of expected joined with " but got " joined with string representation of parser.current_token joined with " at line " joined with string representation of parser.current_line
        Add error_msg to end of parser.errors
        Return false
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming token check used in If/Otherwise dispatch chains where
the grammar branches on which keyword appears next. Distinct from
expect_token because no error is recorded on mismatch - this is a
predicate, not an assertion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single equality check against current_token. Cursor stays put.
@End Implementation
Process called "match_token" that takes parser as ErlangParser, token_type as Integer returns Boolean:
    Return parser.current_token is equal to token_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TOP-LEVEL MODULE PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver that walks until EOF, classifying each top-level
form by its leading token. The -module attribute is special-cased:
its first value becomes the module's name field while the attribute
itself is also kept in attributes for round-trip. The four kinds
(attribute, record, type-decl, function) are mutually exclusive so
the dispatch is a linear If/Otherwise chain.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialises an empty module shell, then loops while current_token !=
TOKEN_EOF. Branches: TOKEN_MINUS -> parse_attribute (and lift -module
name); TOKEN_RECORD -> parse_record; TOKEN_TYPE/OPAQUE/SPEC/CALLBACK
-> parse_type_decl; otherwise -> parse_function. Each parsed form is
appended to its respective list. Returns the assembled ErlangModule.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_erlang_module" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangModule:
    Let module_name be ""
    Let attributes be a list containing nothing
    Let functions be a list containing nothing
    Let records be a list containing nothing
    Let types be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse module forms until EOF
    While parser.current_token is not equal to TOKEN_EOF:
        Note: Module attribute
        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_MINUS:
            Let attr be parse_attribute with parser

            Note: Extract module name from -module attribute
            If attr.attr_type is equal to "module" and length of attr.attr_values is greater than 0:
                Set module_name to attr.attr_values at index 0
            End If

            Add attr to end of attributes

        Note: Record definition
        Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_RECORD:
            Let record be parse_record with parser
            Add record to end of records

        Note: Type declaration
        Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_TYPE or match_token with parser and TOKEN_OPAQUE or match_token with parser and TOKEN_SPEC or match_token with parser and TOKEN_CALLBACK:
            Let type_decl be parse_type_decl with parser
            Add type_decl to end of types

        Note: Function definition
        Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
            Let function be parse_function with parser
            Add function to end of functions

        Note: Skip unexpected tokens
        Otherwise:
            Add "Unexpected token at line " joined with string representation of parser.current_line to end of parser.errors
            Call advance_parser with parser
        End If
    End While

    Return a value of type ErlangModule with
        module_name as module_name,
        attributes as attributes,
        functions as functions,
        records as records,
        types as types
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ATTRIBUTE PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
"-keyword(args)." attribute forms have a uniform outer shape but each
keyword has its own argument grammar (module=atom, export/import=
function list, behaviour=atom, compile=term, default=generic term).
The translator branches on attr_type so each shape gets the correct
parser, keeping the dispatch table inline rather than scattering it
across one routine per attribute kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips the leading "-", captures the attribute name as attr_type, then
optionally enters a "(...)" payload. Inside the parens, loops over
comma-separated values: module/behaviour use the raw lexeme;
export/import dispatch to parse_function_list; compile uses
parse_term; everything else falls through to parse_term. The loop
breaks when no comma follows. Expects closing ")" and the mandatory
terminating "." that ends every Erlang top-level form.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_attribute" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangAttribute:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip -

    Let attr_type be parser.current_lexeme
    Let attr_values be a list containing nothing
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip attribute name

    Note: Parse attribute arguments
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN:
        Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip (

        Note: Parse comma-separated values
        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN:
            While true:
                Note: Parse attribute value based on type
                If attr_type is equal to "module":
                    Add parser.current_lexeme to end of attr_values
                    Call advance_parser with parser

                Otherwise If attr_type is equal to "export" or attr_type is equal to "import":
                    Let export_list be parse_function_list with parser
                    Add export_list to end of attr_values

                Otherwise If attr_type is equal to "behaviour" or attr_type is equal to "behavior":
                    Add parser.current_lexeme to end of attr_values
                    Call advance_parser with parser

                Otherwise If attr_type is equal to "compile":
                    Let compile_opts be parse_term with parser
                    Add compile_opts to end of attr_values

                Otherwise:
                    Let term be parse_term with parser
                    Add term to end of attr_values
                End If

                Note: Check for more values
                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_DOT

    Return a value of type ErlangAttribute with
        attr_type as attr_type,
        attr_values as attr_values,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Parses the "[name/arity, name/arity, ...]" payload that appears in
-export and -import. Each entry is a Name/Arity pair encoded as a
small Dictionary so callers can introspect by key without knowing the
positional layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expects opening "[". If the list is non-empty, loops: captures
function name as string, expects "/", parses arity as Integer
(convert from lexeme), constructs {"name": name, "arity": arity}
Dictionary and appends. Continues while a comma follows; breaks
otherwise. Expects closing "]".
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_function_list" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns List[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Let func_list be a list containing nothing

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACKET

    If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET:
        While true:
            Let func_name be parser.current_lexeme
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_SLASH

            Let arity be convert parser.current_lexeme to Integer
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Let func_info be a dictionary containing:
                "name" as func_name,
                "arity" as arity
            End Dictionary
            Add func_info to end of func_list

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET

    Return func_list
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RECORD PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
"-record(name, { field, field, ... })." is parsed as a fully-bracketed
attribute. Field parsing is delegated to parse_record_field because
each field can carry an optional default value and an optional type
annotation, which is its own sub-grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "-record", expects "(", captures record_name from current
lexeme, expects ",", expects "{". Loops calling parse_record_field
and appending to fields, breaking when no comma follows. Expects
the closing "}", ")", and the terminating ".".
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_record" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangRecord:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip -record

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN

    Let record_name be parser.current_lexeme
    Call advance_parser with parser

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA

    Let fields be a list containing nothing

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACE

    If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE:
        While true:
            Let field be parse_record_field with parser
            Add field to end of fields

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE
    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN
    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_DOT

    Return a value of type ErlangRecord with
        name as record_name,
        fields as fields,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each record field can be bare ("name"), default-valued ("name = expr"),
or fully annotated ("name = expr :: type"). The "=" and "::" markers
are both optional and independent, so the parser must check for each
in sequence without requiring the other.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures the field name from current_lexeme. If TOKEN_ASSIGN follows,
skips and parses a default_value via parse_expression at precedence 0.
If TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON follows, skips and parses field_type via
parse_type_expr. Both default_value and field_type default to null
when their markers are absent.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_record_field" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangRecordField:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Let field_name be parser.current_lexeme
    Call advance_parser with parser

    Let default_value be null
    Let field_type be null

    Note: Parse default value
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ASSIGN:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Set default_value to parse_expression with parser and 0
    End If

    Note: Parse type annotation
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Set field_type to parse_type_expr with parser
    End If

    Return a value of type ErlangRecordField with
        name as field_name,
        default_value as default_value,
        field_type as field_type,
        line as line
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE DECLARATION PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
"-type Name(Vars) :: Expr." is the common shape for type, opaque,
spec, and callback declarations. This routine reads the kind tag
(currently in current_lexeme because parse_erlang_module dispatched
here), then walks the name -> type-variable -> "::" -> body sequence.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures decl_type from current_lexeme. Advances. Reads name from
TOKEN_ATOM (if present). If "(" follows, loops collecting
TOKEN_VARIABLE entries into type_vars until "," fails to match;
expects ")". Expects "::", parses type_expr via parse_type_expr,
expects terminating ".".
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_type_decl" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangTypeDecl:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Let decl_type be parser.current_lexeme
    Call advance_parser with parser

    Let name be ""
    Let type_vars be a list containing nothing
    Let type_expr be null

    Note: Parse name and parameters
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
        Set name to parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser

        Note: Parse type variables
        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN:
            Call advance_parser with parser

            If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN:
                While true:
                    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_VARIABLE:
                        Add parser.current_lexeme to end of type_vars
                        Call advance_parser with parser
                    End If

                    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                        Call advance_parser with parser
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End While
            End If

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN
        End If
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON

    Note: Parse type expression
    Set type_expr to parse_type_expr with parser

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_DOT

    Return a value of type ErlangTypeDecl with
        decl_type as decl_type,
        name as name,
        type_vars as type_vars,
        type_expr as type_expr,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type expressions form their own recursive grammar with six leading-
token shapes (atom, variable, list, tuple, fun, binary) plus a
post-fix union operator. The leaf parser dispatches on the leading
token to pick the shape, then the union check at the end folds
multiple types into a single "union" node if "|" continues to appear.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dispatches on current_token. TOKEN_ATOM: type_kind="atom" (or
"parameterized" if "(" follows with args parsed recursively).
TOKEN_VARIABLE: type_kind="var". TOKEN_LBRACKET: type_kind="list"
with one element_type. TOKEN_LBRACE: type_kind="tuple" with comma-
separated element types. TOKEN_FUN: type_kind="fun" parses arg
types, expects "->", parses return type. TOKEN_LBIN: type_kind=
"binary". After the leaf is parsed, if TOKEN_LIST_CONS (|) follows,
wraps the current type plus subsequent "| type" entries into a
"union" node with type_args holding the alternatives.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_type_expr" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangTypeExpr:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Let type_kind be ""
    Let type_args be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse type expression
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
        Set type_kind to "atom"
        Add parser.current_lexeme to end of type_args
        Call advance_parser with parser

        Note: Parameterized type
        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN:
            Set type_kind to "parameterized"
            Call advance_parser with parser

            If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN:
                While true:
                    Let arg_type be parse_type_expr with parser
                    Add arg_type to end of type_args

                    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                        Call advance_parser with parser
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End While
            End If

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN
        End If

    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_VARIABLE:
        Set type_kind to "var"
        Add parser.current_lexeme to end of type_args
        Call advance_parser with parser

    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Set type_kind to "list"
        Call advance_parser with parser

        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET:
            Let elem_type be parse_type_expr with parser
            Add elem_type to end of type_args
        End If

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET

    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Set type_kind to "tuple"
        Call advance_parser with parser

        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE:
            While true:
                Set elem_type to parse_type_expr with parser
                Add elem_type to end of type_args

                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE

    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_FUN:
        Set type_kind to "fun"
        Call advance_parser with parser

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN

        Note: Parse parameter types
        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN:
            While true:
                Let param_type be parse_type_expr with parser
                Add param_type to end of type_args

                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN
        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ARROW

        Note: Parse return type
        Let return_type be parse_type_expr with parser
        Add return_type to end of type_args

    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBIN:
        Set type_kind to "binary"
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBIN
    End If

    Note: Handle union types (type1() | type2())
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LIST_CONS:
        Let union_types be a list containing nothing
        Add a value of type ErlangTypeExpr with type_kind as type_kind, type_args as type_args, line as line to end of union_types

        While match_token with parser and TOKEN_LIST_CONS:
            Call advance_parser with parser
            Let next_type be parse_type_expr with parser
            Add next_type to end of union_types
        End While

        Set type_kind to "union"
        Set type_args to union_types
    End If

    Return a value of type ErlangTypeExpr with
        type_kind as type_kind,
        type_args as type_args,
        line as line
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Multi-clause function definitions in Erlang are written as
"name(pat) -> body; name(pat) -> body. " - each clause separated by
";" and the entire function terminated by ".". The parser collects
all clauses with the same leading name; arity is derived once from
the first clause's pattern count (Erlang requires all clauses share
arity).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures func_name. Loops: parse_function_clause -> append; if first
clause, lock in arity = clauses[0].patterns.length. If TOKEN_SEMICOLON
follows, advance and verify the next TOKEN_ATOM matches func_name
(otherwise break - it's a different function). Otherwise break.
Expects terminating ".".
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_function" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangFunction:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Let func_name be parser.current_lexeme
    Call advance_parser with parser

    Let clauses be a list containing nothing
    Let arity be 0

    Note: Parse all function clauses
    While true:
        Let clause be parse_function_clause with parser
        Add clause to end of clauses

        Note: Calculate arity from first clause
        If length of clauses is equal to 1:
            Set arity to length of clause.patterns
        End If

        Note: Check for more clauses
        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Note: Next clause must have same name
            If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM or not parser.current_lexeme is equal to func_name:
                Break
            End If

            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_DOT

    Return a value of type ErlangFunction with
        name as func_name,
        arity as arity,
        clauses as clauses,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each clause is "(pat, pat) when guards -> body, body, body". The
patterns, guards (optional), and body are three syntactically
distinct sections separated by ")", "->", and "." respectively.
Body expressions are comma-separated and evaluated in order (the
last one is the clause result).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expects "(". If not immediately ")", loops parse_pattern -> append,
comma or break; expects ")". If TOKEN_WHEN follows, advance and call
parse_guards. Expects "->". Loops parse_expression(min_prec=0) ->
append to body; continues while a comma follows. Returns the
assembled ErlangFunctionClause - the function-level parser is
responsible for the trailing "." or ";".
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_function_clause" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangFunctionClause:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Let patterns be a list containing nothing
    Let guards be a list containing nothing
    Let body be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse parameter patterns
    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN

    If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN:
        While true:
            Let pattern be parse_pattern with parser
            Add pattern to end of patterns

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN

    Note: Parse guard clauses
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_WHEN:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Set guards to parse_guards with parser
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ARROW

    Note: Parse body expressions
    While true:
        Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
        Add expr to end of body

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as guards,
        body as body,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang guards are a two-level grammar: "G1, G2; G3, G4" means
"(G1 and G2) or (G3 and G4)". Parsing as two nested loops mirrors
this structure directly - the outer loop walks over ";"-separated
disjuncts, the inner loop walks over ","-separated conjuncts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Outer loop builds guard_seqs. Inner loop builds guard_seq: parses
each guard expression at precedence 0, appends, continues while
TOKEN_COMMA matches. After inner loop, appends guard_seq to
guard_seqs. If TOKEN_SEMICOLON follows, advances and continues outer
loop; otherwise breaks.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_guards" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns List[List[ErlangExpression]]:
    Let guard_seqs be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse guard sequences separated by semicolons
    While true:
        Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing

        Note: Parse guard tests separated by commas
        While true:
            Let guard_expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
            Add guard_expr to end of guard_seq

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        Add guard_seq to end of guard_seqs

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return guard_seqs
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PATTERN PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Erlang patterns are a syntactic subset of expressions - the same
grammar productions apply but with semantic restrictions (no
function calls, no operators with side effects). This parser
deliberately reuses parse_expression and defers restriction checking
to a later semantic pass so the AST shape is identical between
pattern and expression contexts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates entirely to parse_expression with min_precedence=0.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_pattern" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Return parse_expression with parser and 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION PARSING (with precedence climbing)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lookup table for Erlang's 12-tier operator precedence, encoded as
lower-is-tighter so the precedence-climbing loop in parse_expression
can compare with "<" semantics. The values match the Erlang reference
manual's operator precedence chapter exactly so subtle bugs from
mismatched precedence (e.g. "++/--" binding tighter than "+/-") are
ruled out by construction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequential If-chain. Returns 1 for ":" (remote call), 2 for "#"
(record), 3 for "." (field access), 4 for *///div/rem/band
(multiplicative), 5 for +/-/bor/bxor/bsl/bsr (additive/bitwise),
6 for ++/-- (list concat), 7 for == ///= < > <= >= =:= =/=
(comparison), 8 for andalso, 9 for orelse, 10 for "|" (list cons),
11 for "!" (send), 12 for "=" (match). Returns 999 for any
non-operator token so the parse_expression loop terminates.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_operator_precedence" that takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Precedence levels for Erlang operators
    If token is equal to TOKEN_COLON:
        Return 1  Note: Remote call :
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_HASH:
        Return 2  Note: Record access #
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_DOT:
        Return 3  Note: Map/record field access (not statement dot)
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_STAR or token is equal to TOKEN_SLASH or token is equal to TOKEN_DIV or token is equal to TOKEN_REM or token is equal to TOKEN_BAND:
        Return 4  Note: Multiplicative
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_PLUS or token is equal to TOKEN_MINUS or token is equal to TOKEN_BOR or token is equal to TOKEN_BXOR or token is equal to TOKEN_BSL or token is equal to TOKEN_BSR:
        Return 5  Note: Additive and bitwise
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_PLUS_PLUS or token is equal to TOKEN_MINUS_MINUS:
        Return 6  Note: List concatenation
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_EQUAL_EQUAL or token is equal to TOKEN_SLASH_EQUAL or token is equal to TOKEN_LESS or token is equal to TOKEN_GREATER or token is equal to TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL or token is equal to TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL or token is equal to TOKEN_EXACT_EQUAL or token is equal to TOKEN_EXACT_NOT_EQUAL:
        Return 7  Note: Comparison
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_ANDALSO:
        Return 8  Note: Logical and
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_ORELSE:
        Return 9  Note: Logical or
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_LIST_CONS:
        Return 10  Note: List cons |
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_SEND:
        Return 11  Note: Send message !
    End If

    If token is equal to TOKEN_ASSIGN:
        Return 12  Note: Match =
    End If

    Return 999  Note: Not an operator
End Process

@Reasoning:
Three Erlang operators are right-associative: "=" (match), "!" (send),
and "|" (list cons). The precedence-climbing parser needs this
distinction to compute the next-iteration min_precedence correctly:
for right-associative operators the right operand can re-use the same
precedence, for left-associative ones it must be strictly higher.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single If check against TOKEN_ASSIGN, TOKEN_SEND, or TOKEN_LIST_CONS.
Returns true only for those three.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_right_associative" that takes token as Integer returns Boolean:
    If token is equal to TOKEN_ASSIGN or token is equal to TOKEN_SEND or token is equal to TOKEN_LIST_CONS:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Precedence-climbing implementation (Pratt-style) - parses any
expression at or tighter than the given min_precedence. The leaf
operand comes from parse_primary_expression; then the loop greedily
consumes binary operators whose precedence beats min_precedence,
re-invoking itself for the right operand with the right
min_precedence (op_prec or op_prec-1 for right- vs left-associative
respectively).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls parse_primary_expression for the left leaf. Loops: looks up
op_precedence for current_token; breaks if not better than
min_precedence. Captures op_token / op_lexeme / line, advances past
the operator, computes next_min_prec (op_precedence for right-assoc,
op_precedence-1 for left-assoc), recurses to parse right at that
precedence, builds an ErlangExpression with expr_type="op" carrying
{"operator", "left", "right"} and stores as the new left.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser, min_precedence as Integer returns ErlangExpression:
    Let left be parse_primary_expression with parser

    Note: Precedence climbing for binary operators
    While true:
        Let op_precedence be get_operator_precedence with parser.current_token

        If op_precedence is greater than or equal to min_precedence:
            Break
        End If

        Let op_token be parser.current_token
        Let op_lexeme be parser.current_lexeme
        Let line be parser.current_line
        Call advance_parser with parser

        Note: Handle right associativity
        Let next_min_prec be op_precedence
        If not is_right_associative with op_token:
            Set next_min_prec to op_precedence minus 1
        End If

        Let right be parse_expression with parser and next_min_prec

        Note: Create binary operator expression
        Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
            "operator" as op_lexeme,
            "left" as left,
            "right" as right
        End Dictionary

        Set left to a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "op",
            expr_data as expr_data,
            line as line
    End While

    Return left
End Process

@Reasoning:
The leaf parser dispatches on the leading token among ~17 productions
that can start a primary expression. After the leaf is built, postfix
operations (function call, record access) are folded in via
parse_postfix so the same routine handles both "x" and "x(...)" and
"x#rec.field" uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Linear If/Otherwise If chain on current_token: TOKEN_ATOM -> atom
literal; TOKEN_VARIABLE -> var; TOKEN_INTEGER/FLOAT/CHAR/STRING ->
typed literal with value converted from the lexeme; TOKEN_LBRACKET ->
delegate to parse_list (which also detects list comprehensions);
TOKEN_LBRACE -> parse_tuple; TOKEN_LBIN -> parse_binary; TOKEN_LPAREN
-> parenthesised sub-expression; TOKEN_FUN/CASE/IF/RECEIVE/TRY/BEGIN
-> respective sub-parser; unary +/-/bnot/not -> unary_op with operand
parsed at primary level (so unary binds tightest); TOKEN_QUESTION ->
macro reference; TOKEN_HASH -> parse_record_expr. On unrecognised
token records a diagnostic and produces an "error"-typed expression
so the AST is still well-formed. Always passes the result through
parse_postfix to attach trailing calls / record accesses.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_primary_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Let expr_type be ""
    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing nothing

    Note: Atom literal
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
        Set expr_type to "atom"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser

    Note: Variable
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_VARIABLE:
        Set expr_type to "var"
        Set expr_data at key "name" to parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser

    Note: Integer literal
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_INTEGER:
        Set expr_type to "integer"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to convert parser.current_lexeme to Integer
        Call advance_parser with parser

    Note: Float literal
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_FLOAT:
        Set expr_type to "float"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to convert parser.current_lexeme to Float
        Call advance_parser with parser

    Note: Character literal
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_CHAR:
        Set expr_type to "char"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser

    Note: String literal
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_STRING:
        Set expr_type to "string"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser

    Note: List literal
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Return parse_list with parser

    Note: Tuple literal
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Return parse_tuple with parser

    Note: Binary literal
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBIN:
        Return parse_binary with parser

    Note: Parenthesized expression
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN
        Return expr

    Note: Fun expression (anonymous function)
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_FUN:
        Return parse_fun_expression with parser

    Note: Case expression
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_CASE:
        Return parse_case_expression with parser

    Note: If expression
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_IF:
        Return parse_if_expression with parser

    Note: Receive expression
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_RECEIVE:
        Return parse_receive_expression with parser

    Note: Try expression
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_TRY:
        Return parse_try_expression with parser

    Note: Begin-end block
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_BEGIN:
        Return parse_begin_expression with parser

    Note: Unary operators
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_MINUS or match_token with parser and TOKEN_PLUS or match_token with parser and TOKEN_BNOT or match_token with parser and TOKEN_NOT:
        Let op_lexeme be parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Let operand be parse_primary_expression with parser

        Set expr_type to "unary_op"
        Set expr_data at key "operator" to op_lexeme
        Set expr_data at key "operand" to operand

    Note: Macro variable
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_QUESTION:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Let macro_name be parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser

        Set expr_type to "macro"
        Set expr_data at key "name" to macro_name

    Note: Record creation or access
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_HASH:
        Return parse_record_expr with parser

    Otherwise:
        Add "Unexpected token in expression at line " joined with string representation of line to end of parser.errors
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Set expr_type to "error"
    End If

    Note: Handle postfix operations (function calls, record access)
    Let result be a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as expr_type,
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as line

    Set result to parse_postfix with parser and result

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Folds chained postfix operations onto a leaf expression. Only two
postfix kinds in Erlang: function call "expr(args)" and record field
access "expr#name". Both can chain (e.g. "module:func()(arg)"), so
the loop continues until neither marker is present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops on current_token. TOKEN_LPAREN: consumes "(", parses comma-
separated args via parse_expression(min_prec=0), expects ")", wraps
result in expr_type="call" with {"function": result, "arguments":
args}. TOKEN_HASH: consumes "#" and the field name lexeme, wraps in
expr_type="record_access" with {"record", "field"}. Any other token
breaks the loop. Returns the (possibly-chained) wrapped expression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_postfix" that takes parser as ErlangParser, expr as ErlangExpression returns ErlangExpression:
    Let result be expr

    While true:
        Note: Function call
        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN:
            Let line be parser.current_line
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Let args be a list containing nothing

            If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN:
                While true:
                    Let arg be parse_expression with parser and 0
                    Add arg to end of args

                    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                        Call advance_parser with parser
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End While
            End If

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN

            Let call_data be a dictionary containing:
                "function" as result,
                "arguments" as args
            End Dictionary

            Set result to a value of type ErlangExpression with
                expr_type as "call",
                expr_data as call_data,
                line as line

        Note: Record field access
        Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_HASH:
            Set line to parser.current_line
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Let field_name be parser.current_lexeme
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Let access_data be a dictionary containing:
                "record" as result,
                "field" as field_name
            End Dictionary

            Set result to a value of type ErlangExpression with
                expr_type as "record_access",
                expr_data as access_data,
                line as line

        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COMPOUND EXPRESSION PARSING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
List literals "[A, B, C]" share syntax with list comprehensions
"[Expr || Gen, Filt]" and improper lists "[H | T]". The parser tries
the plain-list path first, then detects the post-fix "||" for
comprehensions or the "|" tail marker mid-walk. This unified entry
point keeps the dispatch simple at the caller level.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes "[". If non-empty, loops parse_expression -> append. On
TOKEN_COMMA: continue. On TOKEN_LIST_CONS ("|"): parse the tail
expression and break. Otherwise break. Expects "]". If exactly one
element was parsed and TOKEN_DOUBLE_LIST_CONS ("||") follows,
delegates to parse_list_comprehension with that element as the
template. Otherwise wraps elements+tail into a "list" ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_list" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip [

    Let elements be a list containing nothing
    Let tail be null

    If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET:
        Note: Parse list elements
        While true:
            Let elem be parse_expression with parser and 0
            Add elem to end of elements

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LIST_CONS:
                Note: List with tail [H|T]
                Call advance_parser with parser
                Set tail to parse_expression with parser and 0
                Break
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET

    Note: Check for list comprehension
    If length of elements is equal to 1 and match_token with parser and TOKEN_DOUBLE_LIST_CONS:
        Return parse_list_comprehension with parser and elements at index 0
    End If

    Let list_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as elements,
        "tail" as tail
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "list",
        expr_data as list_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuples are fixed-size heterogeneous collections in Erlang, written
with curly braces. Unlike lists, no tail marker exists - all elements
are positional.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes "{". If non-empty, loops parse_expression -> append elements,
continuing while a comma follows. Expects "}". Wraps elements into a
"tuple" ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_tuple" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip {

    Let elements be a list containing nothing

    If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE:
        While true:
            Let elem be parse_expression with parser and 0
            Add elem to end of elements

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE

    Let tuple_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as elements
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "tuple",
        expr_data as tuple_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's binary literal "<<seg, seg, seg>>" supports per-segment Size
and Type specifiers (e.g. "Val:8/integer-unsigned"). Each segment is
a sub-grammar consisting of value, optional ":Size", optional
"/Type-Type-Type". Like list, binary literal syntax also doubles as
binary comprehension when "||" follows the closing ">>".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes "<<". Loops segments: parses value expression. If ":"
follows, parses size expression; if "/" follows that, loops over
TOKEN_ATOM specifiers separated by "-" (binary specifier syntax).
Each segment is {"value", "size", "specifiers"} appended to segments
list. Comma continues, otherwise breaks. Expects ">>". If exactly
one segment and TOKEN_DOUBLE_LIST_CONS follows, dispatches to
parse_binary_comprehension. Otherwise wraps segments into a "binary"
ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_binary" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip <<

    Let segments be a list containing nothing

    If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBIN:
        While true:
            Let value be parse_expression with parser and 0

            Note: Parse binary segment specifiers (Size, Type)
            Let size be null
            Let specifiers be a list containing nothing

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COLON:
                Call advance_parser with parser
                Set size to parse_expression with parser and 0

                Note: Parse type specifiers
                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SLASH:
                    Call advance_parser with parser

                    While true:
                        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
                            Add parser.current_lexeme to end of specifiers
                            Call advance_parser with parser
                        End If

                        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_MINUS:
                            Call advance_parser with parser
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End While
                End If
            End If

            Let segment_data be a dictionary containing:
                "value" as value,
                "size" as size,
                "specifiers" as specifiers
            End Dictionary

            Add segment_data to end of segments

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBIN

    Note: Check for binary comprehension
    If length of segments is equal to 1 and match_token with parser and TOKEN_DOUBLE_LIST_CONS:
        Return parse_binary_comprehension with parser and segments at index 0
    End If

    Let binary_data be a dictionary containing:
        "segments" as segments
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "binary",
        expr_data as binary_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
"fun" in Erlang introduces three distinct forms: (1) remote
reference "fun Mod:Fun/Arity", (2) local reference "fun Fun/Arity",
and (3) anonymous function "fun (Args) -> Body end" with optional
multiple clauses. The parser dispatches on the token after "fun":
TOKEN_ATOM followed by ":" or "/" picks (1) or (2); TOKEN_LPAREN
picks (3).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
After "fun": TOKEN_ATOM branch reads first_name then dispatches on
":" (remote_ref - reads function name then "/" arity), "/" (local_ref
- reads arity directly), or records error. TOKEN_LPAREN branch parses
multi-clause anonymous function: each clause matches the
parse_function_clause grammar (patterns, optional when-guards, "->",
body), clauses separated by ";". Expects "end" at the end. The
final expression carries expr_data["type"] in {"remote_ref",
"local_ref", "anonymous"} for the lowering pass.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_fun_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip fun

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing nothing

    Note: Named function reference: fun Module:Function/Arity or fun Function/Arity
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
        Let first_name be parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COLON:
            Note: Remote function reference: fun Module:Function/Arity
            Call advance_parser with parser
            Let func_name be parser.current_lexeme
            Call advance_parser with parser
            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_SLASH
            Let arity be convert parser.current_lexeme to Integer
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Set expr_data at key "type" to "remote_ref"
            Set expr_data at key "module" to first_name
            Set expr_data at key "function" to func_name
            Set expr_data at key "arity" to arity

        Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SLASH:
            Note: Local function reference: fun Function/Arity
            Call advance_parser with parser
            Set arity to convert parser.current_lexeme to Integer
            Call advance_parser with parser

            Set expr_data at key "type" to "local_ref"
            Set expr_data at key "function" to first_name
            Set expr_data at key "arity" to arity

        Otherwise:
            Add "Expected : or / after function name in fun expression" to end of parser.errors
        End If

    Note: Anonymous function: fun (Args) -> Body end
    Otherwise If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN:
        Let clauses be a list containing nothing

        While true:
            Let clause_line be parser.current_line
            Let patterns be a list containing nothing
            Let guards be a list containing nothing
            Let body be a list containing nothing

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LPAREN

            Note: Parse parameters
            If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN:
                While true:
                    Let pattern be parse_pattern with parser
                    Add pattern to end of patterns

                    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                        Call advance_parser with parser
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End While
            End If

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RPAREN

            Note: Parse guards
            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_WHEN:
                Call advance_parser with parser
                Set guards to parse_guards with parser
            End If

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ARROW

            Note: Parse body
            While true:
                Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
                Add expr to end of body

                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While

            Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
                patterns as patterns,
                guards as guards,
                body as body,
                line as clause_line

            Add clause to end of clauses

            Note: Check for more clauses
            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_END

        Set expr_data at key "type" to "anonymous"
        Set expr_data at key "clauses" to clauses
    End If

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "fun",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
"case X of P1 -> B1; P2 -> B2 end" is Erlang's pattern-match
expression. The scrutinee X is evaluated once; each clause is
checked in order until one matches. Reuses parse_case_clause for
each arm to keep the clause grammar consistent with try-of catch
arms (which share the same shape).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "case". Parses scrutinee via parse_expression. Expects "of".
Loops until TOKEN_END, parsing each clause via parse_case_clause and
optionally consuming a separating ";". Expects "end". Wraps into a
"case" ErlangExpression with {"scrutinee", "clauses"}.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_case_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip case

    Let scrutinee be parse_expression with parser and 0

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_OF

    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse case clauses
    While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_END:
        Let clause be parse_case_clause with parser
        Add clause to end of clauses

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        End If
    End While

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_END

    Let case_data be a dictionary containing:
        "scrutinee" as scrutinee,
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "case",
        expr_data as case_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
A case clause is structurally a single-pattern function clause
("Pat when Guards -> Body"). Reusing ErlangFunctionClause as the
return type (rather than introducing a separate ErlangCaseClause)
keeps the HIR lowering uniform between case arms and function
clauses, which is the right model since both compile to pattern
match instructions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Parses a single pattern via parse_pattern, wraps in a one-element
patterns list. If "when" follows, parses guards via parse_guards.
Expects "->". Loops parse_expression to collect comma-separated body
expressions. Returns the ErlangFunctionClause shape.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_case_clause" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangFunctionClause:
    Let line be parser.current_line

    Let pattern be parse_pattern with parser
    Let patterns be a list containing pattern

    Let guards be a list containing nothing
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_WHEN:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Set guards to parse_guards with parser
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ARROW

    Let body be a list containing nothing
    While true:
        Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
        Add expr to end of body

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as guards,
        body as body,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's "if Guards -> Body; Guards -> Body end" is NOT C-style if -
there is no expression, only guards. The first clause with all-true
guards wins; if none match the runtime raises a no_clause error.
Each "if-clause" reuses the function-clause shape with an empty
patterns list because all dispatch is guard-only.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "if". Loops until TOKEN_END: parses guards via parse_guards,
expects "->", reads comma-separated body expressions. Builds an
ErlangFunctionClause with empty patterns, the guards, and the body.
Optional ";" between clauses. Expects "end". Wraps the clauses list
into an "if" ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_if_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip if

    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse if clauses (guards only, no patterns)
    While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_END:
        Let clause_line be parser.current_line
        Let guards be parse_guards with parser

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ARROW

        Let body be a list containing nothing
        While true:
            Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
            Add expr to end of body

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as a list containing nothing,
            guards as guards,
            body as body,
            line as clause_line

        Add clause to end of clauses

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        End If
    End While

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_END

    Let if_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "if",
        expr_data as if_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
"receive Pat -> Body; ... after Timeout -> Body end" is the message-
queue inspection primitive that defines Erlang's actor model. The
after clause is optional and provides a timeout / default branch.
Parser uses parse_case_clause for the main arms because the pattern
syntax matches case clauses exactly; the after branch is parsed
separately because its guard slot is the timeout expression rather
than a guard list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "receive". Loops until TOKEN_AFTER or TOKEN_END: parses each
clause via parse_case_clause and appends. Optional ";" between
clauses. If TOKEN_AFTER follows, parses after_timeout via
parse_expression, expects "->", reads comma-separated after_body
expressions. Expects "end". Wraps {"clauses", "after_timeout",
"after_body"} into a "receive" ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_receive_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip receive

    Let clauses be a list containing nothing
    Let after_timeout be null
    Let after_body be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse receive clauses
    While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_AFTER and not match_token with parser and TOKEN_END:
        Let clause be parse_case_clause with parser
        Add clause to end of clauses

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse optional after clause
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_AFTER:
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Set after_timeout to parse_expression with parser and 0
        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ARROW

        While true:
            Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
            Add expr to end of after_body

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_END

    Let receive_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses,
        "after_timeout" as after_timeout,
        "after_body" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "receive",
        expr_data as receive_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
The full Erlang try expression: "try Body of Pat -> Result catch
Class:Pat -> Handler after Cleanup end". All four sub-sections (of,
catch, after) are optional, leading to a four-stage parse where each
stage looks ahead at the section terminator before deciding whether
to descend. The catch pattern's "Class:Pat" form (used for
'exit', 'error', 'throw' qualifiers) is encoded by promoting the
first pattern to exception_class if a colon follows.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "try". Parses comma-separated try_body expressions until of/
catch/after. If TOKEN_OF: loops until catch/after/end, parsing each
arm via parse_case_clause -> of_clauses. If TOKEN_CATCH: loops until
after/end. For each catch arm: parses initial pattern; if ":"
follows, promotes that pattern into exception_class and parses a new
exception_pattern; optional when-guards; "->"; comma-separated body.
Stores {"exception_class", "exception_pattern", "guards", "body"}
per arm. If TOKEN_AFTER: parses comma-separated after_body until
end. Expects "end". Wraps the four lists into a "try" ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_try_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip try

    Note: Parse try body
    Let try_body be a list containing nothing
    While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_OF and not match_token with parser and TOKEN_CATCH and not match_token with parser and TOKEN_AFTER:
        Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
        Add expr to end of try_body

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse optional 'of' clauses
    Let of_clauses be a list containing nothing
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_OF:
        Call advance_parser with parser

        While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_CATCH and not match_token with parser and TOKEN_AFTER and not match_token with parser and TOKEN_END:
            Let clause be parse_case_clause with parser
            Add clause to end of of_clauses

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Note: Parse catch clauses
    Let catch_clauses be a list containing nothing
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_CATCH:
        Call advance_parser with parser

        While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_AFTER and not match_token with parser and TOKEN_END:
            Let clause_line be parser.current_line

            Note: Parse exception pattern (Class:Pattern or Pattern)
            Let exception_class be null
            Let exception_pattern be parse_pattern with parser

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COLON:
                Call advance_parser with parser
                Set exception_class to exception_pattern
                Set exception_pattern to parse_pattern with parser
            End If

            Let guards be a list containing nothing
            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_WHEN:
                Call advance_parser with parser
                Set guards to parse_guards with parser
            End If

            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ARROW

            Let body be a list containing nothing
            While true:
                Set expr to parse_expression with parser and 0
                Add expr to end of body

                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While

            Let catch_data be a dictionary containing:
                "exception_class" as exception_class,
                "exception_pattern" as exception_pattern,
                "guards" as guards,
                "body" as body
            End Dictionary

            Add catch_data to end of catch_clauses

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_SEMICOLON:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Note: Parse optional after clause
    Let after_body be a list containing nothing
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_AFTER:
        Call advance_parser with parser

        While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_END:
            Set expr to parse_expression with parser and 0
            Add expr to end of after_body

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_END

    Let try_data be a dictionary containing:
        "try_body" as try_body,
        "of_clauses" as of_clauses,
        "catch_clauses" as catch_clauses,
        "after_body" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "try",
        expr_data as try_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
"begin ... end" groups multiple expressions into a single
expression with the value of the last expression. Useful for
sequencing side effects inside contexts that demand a single
expression (e.g. inside another expression). HIR represents this
as a typed "begin" node whose lowering is a direct sequence.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "begin". Loops until TOKEN_END collecting comma-separated
parse_expression results into body. Expects "end". Wraps body
into a "begin" ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_begin_expression" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip begin

    Let body be a list containing nothing

    While not match_token with parser and TOKEN_END:
        Let expr be parse_expression with parser and 0
        Add expr to end of body

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_END

    Let begin_data be a dictionary containing:
        "body" as body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "begin",
        expr_data as begin_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[Template || Qualifier, Qualifier, ...]" - the qualifiers are
either generators (Pat <- List, Pat <= Binary) or filters
(boolean expressions). The template is already parsed by parse_list
when it detected the "||" so this routine focuses only on the
qualifier list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "||". Loops parsing qualifiers: uses peek_token+1 to look two
tokens ahead - if it is TOKEN_LARROW, treats as generator (parse
pattern, expect "<-", parse list expression); TOKEN_LBINARROW
("<="), treats as binary_generator; otherwise as filter (single
boolean expression). Each qualifier is appended as a small Dict
with "type" tag. Comma continues. Expects "]". Wraps {"template",
"qualifiers"} into a "list_comprehension" ErlangExpression.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_list_comprehension" that takes parser as ErlangParser, template as ErlangExpression returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip ||

    Let qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse comprehension qualifiers (generators and filters)
    While true:
        Note: Generator: Pattern <- List
        If peek_token with parser and 1 is equal to TOKEN_LARROW:
            Let pattern be parse_pattern with parser
            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LARROW
            Let list_expr be parse_expression with parser and 0

            Let generator_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "generator",
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "list" as list_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add generator_data to end of qualifiers

        Note: Binary generator: Pattern <= Binary
        Otherwise If peek_token with parser and 1 is equal to TOKEN_LBINARROW:
            Set pattern to parse_pattern with parser
            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LBINARROW
            Let binary_expr be parse_expression with parser and 0

            Set generator_data to a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "binary_generator",
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "binary" as binary_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add generator_data to end of qualifiers

        Note: Filter: BoolExpression
        Otherwise:
            Let filter_expr be parse_expression with parser and 0

            Let filter_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as filter_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_data to end of qualifiers
        End If

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET

    Let comp_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "list_comprehension",
        expr_data as comp_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
"<<Template || Qualifier, Qualifier, ...>>" - binary comprehension
produces a new binary. Qualifier grammar is identical to list
comprehension; only the closing delimiter ("/>" vs "]") and the
result type differ. The two routines are intentionally kept
separate (rather than parameterised) because the template parameter
type differs - binary template is Dict, list template is
ErlangExpression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Identical to parse_list_comprehension except: takes the template as
a binary-segment Dict, expects TOKEN_RBIN (">>") instead of "]",
and wraps result with expr_type="binary_comprehension".
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_binary_comprehension" that takes parser as ErlangParser, template as Dictionary[String, Any] returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip ||

    Let qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    Note: Parse comprehension qualifiers (same as list comprehension)
    While true:
        If peek_token with parser and 1 is equal to TOKEN_LARROW:
            Let pattern be parse_pattern with parser
            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LARROW
            Let list_expr be parse_expression with parser and 0

            Let generator_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "generator",
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "list" as list_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add generator_data to end of qualifiers

        Otherwise If peek_token with parser and 1 is equal to TOKEN_LBINARROW:
            Set pattern to parse_pattern with parser
            Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_LBINARROW
            Let binary_expr be parse_expression with parser and 0

            Set generator_data to a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "binary_generator",
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "binary" as binary_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add generator_data to end of qualifiers

        Otherwise:
            Let filter_expr be parse_expression with parser and 0

            Let filter_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as filter_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_data to end of qualifiers
        End If

        If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
            Call advance_parser with parser
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBIN

    Let comp_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "binary_comprehension",
        expr_data as comp_data,
        line as line
End Process

@Reasoning:
"#name{...}" can mean three things in Erlang: record creation
"#name{field=value}", record update "#name{Base | field=value}", or
field index "#name.field". The leading "#" plus record name is shared;
the disambiguation comes from the token after the record name (either
"{" with optional update piping, or ".").
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Skips "#", captures record_name from current_lexeme. If "{" follows:
detects update form by parsing a leading expression that is NOT an
atom-followed-by-equals (heuristic: any non-RBRACE non-ATOM token is
the base of an update); when present, expects "|" before fields.
Loops field assignments "name = expr". Expects "}". Wraps into
expr_type="record_create" (or "record_update" if base_record was
parsed). Implementation captures fields, base_record, and name into
the expr_data Dict.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_record_expr" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns ErlangExpression:
    Let line be parser.current_line
    Call advance_parser with parser  Note: Skip #

    Let record_name be parser.current_lexeme
    Call advance_parser with parser

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as record_name
    End Dictionary

    Note: Record creation or update
    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Call advance_parser with parser

        Let fields be a list containing nothing
        Let base_record be null

        Note: Check for record update: #record{BaseExpr | field=value}
        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE and not match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
            Set base_record to parse_expression with parser and 0

            If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LIST_CONS:
                Call advance_parser with parser
            End If
        End If

        Note: Parse field assignments
        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE:
            While true:
                Let field_name be parser.current_lexeme
                Call advance_parser with parser

                Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_ASSIGN

                Let field_value be parse_expression with parser and 0

                Let field_data be a dictionary containing:
                    "name" as field_name,
                    "value" as field_value
                End Dictionary

                Add field_data to end of fields

                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE

        Set expr_data at key "fields" to fields
        Set expr_data at key "base" to base_record

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "record_create",
            expr_data as expr_data,
            line as line

    Note: Record field access is handled in postfix parsing
    Otherwise:
        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "record_name",
            expr_data as expr_data,
            line as line
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang "term" syntax (used in attribute arguments and the IO term
format) is a restricted grammar that only allows atoms, integers,
strings, lists, and tuples - no variables, no function calls, no
operators. This parser stays minimal because terms are static
data and never need expression-level features.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dispatches on current_token: TOKEN_ATOM/TOKEN_STRING return the raw
lexeme; TOKEN_INTEGER returns the converted integer; TOKEN_LBRACKET
recurses into comma-separated parse_term calls building a List;
TOKEN_LBRACE same but builds a tuple-list (the caller distinguishes
list vs tuple by context). On any other token returns null. Returns
Integer because Runa pointers are integers and the function can
return either a string handle, an integer, or a list pointer.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_term" that takes parser as ErlangParser returns Integer:

    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_ATOM:
        Let value be parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Return value
    End If

    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_INTEGER:
        Set value to convert parser.current_lexeme to Integer
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Return value
    End If

    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_STRING:
        Set value to parser.current_lexeme
        Call advance_parser with parser
        Return value
    End If

    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACKET:
        Let list be a list containing nothing
        Call advance_parser with parser

        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET:
            While true:
                Let elem be parse_term with parser
                Add elem to end of list

                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACKET
        Return list
    End If

    If match_token with parser and TOKEN_LBRACE:
        Let tuple be a list containing nothing
        Call advance_parser with parser

        If not match_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE:
            While true:
                Set elem to parse_term with parser
                Add elem to end of tuple

                If match_token with parser and TOKEN_COMMA:
                    Call advance_parser with parser
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If

        Call expect_token with parser and TOKEN_RBRACE
        Return tuple
    End If

    Note: Default: return null
    Return null
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PARSER ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single public entry point for the entire Erlang frontend. Encapsulates
the parser-state-allocation step so callers (the translation driver)
do not need to know about the ErlangParser type. Parse errors are
collected on parser.errors and walked at the end for diagnostic
reporting; the partial module is still returned so the next pass
can decide whether the diagnostics are recoverable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls create_erlang_parser with the three parallel arrays. Calls
parse_erlang_module to walk the input. After the walk, if
parser.errors is non-empty, iterates the diagnostic strings. Returns
the module unconditionally - error recovery is the caller's
responsibility.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_erlang" that takes tokens as Integer, lexemes as Integer, line_numbers as Integer returns ErlangModule:
    Let parser be create_erlang_parser with tokens, lexemes, line_numbers
    Let module be parse_erlang_module with parser

    Note: Report any parse errors
    If length of parser.errors is greater than 0:
        Note: Errors detected during parsing
        For Each error in parser.errors:
            Note: Error: {error}
        End For
    End If

    Return module
End Process
